    Flavia Neapolis, Palestine [now Nāblus]; died c. 165, Rome [Italy]; feast day June 1), one 
    of the most important of the Greek philosopher-Apologists in the early Christian church. His writings
    represent the first positive encounter of Christian revelation with Greek philosophy 
    and laid the basis for a theology of history)</mads:note>
